  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is it the norm to put your degrees in your email signature?",
  "response": "Whether to include degrees in your email signature depends on the norms of your industry, profession, and workplace culture. Here are some general guidelines to help you decide:\n\n### **When to Include Degrees**\n1. **Professional or Academic Settings**: In fields like academia, medicine, law, or research, it\u2019s common to include degrees (e.g., PhD, MD, JD) to establish credibility and expertise.\n2. **Formal Communication**: In formal or professional contexts, listing degrees can convey professionalism and qualifications.\n3. **Networking or External Communication**: When emailing people outside your organization, especially in professional or academic circles, including degrees can help establish your qualifications.\n4. **Cultural Expectations**: In some regions or industries, it\u2019s expected or respected to include degrees.\n\n### **When to Omit Degrees**\n1. **Internal Communication**: If you\u2019re emailing colleagues within your organization, omitting degrees can seem less formal and more approachable.\n2. **Non-Professional Contexts**: In creative or casual industries, degrees may not carry the same weight, and their inclusion might seem unnecessary or pretentious.\n3. **Redundant Information**: If your job title or role already implies your expertise (e.g., \"Professor,\" \"Surgeon\"), adding degrees may be redundant.\n\n### **Tips for Including Degrees**\n- **Be Concise**: List only your highest or most relevant degrees (e.g., \"Jane Doe, PhD\" instead of listing all your degrees).\n- **Use Abbreviations**: Use standard abbreviations (e.g., MBA, MSc, EdD) to keep your signature clean.\n- **Consider Context**: Tailor your signature based on the recipient and purpose of the email.\n\nUltimately, the decision should align with your professional identity and the expectations of your audience. If in doubt, observe what others in your field or organization are doing.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
